## 2026-02-21 — VS Code port forwarding uses IPv6 but backend only binds IPv4

### Symptom
- Port 8000 is forwarded in VS Code, but browser requests still timeout
- `curl http://127.0.0.1:8000` from server → 200 ✅
- `curl http://[::1]:8000` from server → Connection refused ❌
- VS Code port forwarding may route through `::1` (IPv6 loopback)

### Root Cause
Backend `main.py` bound Hypercorn to `0.0.0.0:8000` (IPv4 only). VS Code Remote SSH port forwarding can use IPv6 `::1` internally, which has no listener.

Initial fix attempt — binding to BOTH `0.0.0.0:8000` and `[::]:8000` — crashed with `OSError: [Errno 98] Address already in use` because Linux dual-stack sockets make `[::]` implicitly cover IPv4 too.

### Fix
Changed `backend/main.py` to bind only to `[::]:8000` (dual-stack). On Linux, this accepts both IPv4 and IPv6 connections:
```python
config.bind = [f"[::]:{settings.PORT}"]
```

### Verification
- `curl http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/health` → 200 ✅
- `curl http://[::1]:8000/api/health` → 200 ✅
- CORS OPTIONS preflight via IPv6 → 204 ✅
- POST /api/icebreaker/analyze via IPv6 → 200 with full data ✅

### Files Changed
- `backend/main.py`

